   369→            <h2>Documentation Navigation</h2>
   370→
   371→            <p>
   372→                This formalization is documented across multiple interconnected resources. Each serves a distinct purpose
   373→                in understanding the mathematical result, its formalization, and the proof architecture.
   374→            </p>
   375→
   376→            <h3>Quick Links to Major Results</h3>
   377→
   378→            <p>
   379→                <strong>Main Theorem:</strong>
   380→                <a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/MainTheorem.html#rotated_roots_yield_chebyshev" style="color: #3498db;">API Docs</a> |
   381→                <a href="./blueprint/sect0001.html" style="color: #3498db;">Blueprint §1</a>
   382→            </p>
   383→
   384→            <p>
   385→                <strong>Power Sum Invariance (φ-independence):</strong>
   386→                <a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/PowerSums.html#powerSumCos_invariant" style="color: #3498db;">API Docs</a> |
   387→                <a href="./blueprint/sect0004.html" style="color: #3498db;">Blueprint §4</a>
   388→            </p>
   389→
   390→            <p>
   391→                <strong>Discrete Orthogonality:</strong>
   392→                <a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/ChebyshevOrthogonality.html" style="color: #3498db;">Module Documentation</a> |
   393→                <a href="./blueprint/sect0005.html" style="color: #3498db;">Blueprint §5</a>
   394→            </p>
   395→
   396→            <p>
   397→                <strong>Newton's Identities Application:</strong>
   398→                <a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/NewtonIdentities.html" style="color: #3498db;">Module Documentation</a> |
   399→                <a href="./blueprint/sect0006.html" style="color: #3498db;">Blueprint §6</a>
   400→            </p>
   401→
   402→            <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
   403→                <strong>Visual Proof Structure:</strong> The <a href="./graph/" style="color: #3498db;">dependency graph</a>
   404→                provides an interactive visualization of all 200+ definitions, lemmas, and theorems, showing how foundational
   405→                results in discrete orthogonality and polynomial algebra combine to establish the main theorem.
   406→            </p>
   407→
   408→            <h2>Proof Strategy</h2>
   409→
   410→            <p>
   411→                The verification establishes that rotated roots and Chebyshev roots share identical power sums for all
   412→                positive degrees, which by Newton's identities implies they generate polynomials differing only by a
   413→                constant term. This approach reduces the geometric claim to an algebraic invariant (power sums), then
   414→                applies classical polynomial algebra to reach the conclusion.
   415→            </p>
   416→
   417→            <h3>Critical Proofs</h3>
   418→
   419→            <p>
   420→                <strong>Power Sum Invariance (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/PowerSums.html#powerSumCos_invariant" style="color: #3498db;">powerSumCos_invariant</a>):</strong>
   421→                The cornerstone of the entire proof. This establishes that ∑cos<sup>m</sup>(φ + 2πk/N) is independent of the
   422→                rotation angle φ for all m ≥ 1. The proof exploits the fact that cos(θ) = (e<sup>iθ</sup> + e<sup>-iθ</sup>)/2,
   423→                converting cosine powers into sums of complex exponentials. These exponential sums telescope to zero by discrete
   424→                orthogonality unless specific divisibility conditions hold, yielding the φ-independence. Without this result,
   425→                there would be no connection between rotated roots and Chebyshev polynomials.
   426→            </p>
   427→
   428→            <p>
   429→                <strong>Discrete Orthogonality (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/ChebyshevOrthogonality.html" style="color: #3498db;">ChebyshevOrthogonality module</a>):</strong>
   430→                Proves that ∑<sub>k=0</sub><sup>N-1</sup> exp(2πikm/N) = 0 for 0 < m < N and equals N when m = 0 or N divides m.
   431→                This is the discrete analog of continuous Fourier orthogonality on the circle. The proof uses properties of
   432→                geometric series and the fact that N-th roots of unity satisfy ω<sup>N</sup> = 1. This orthogonality is what
   433→                causes most terms in the power sum expansion to vanish, leaving only the φ-independent contributions. It connects
   434→                harmonic analysis (orthogonality relations) to polynomial root behavior.
   435→            </p>
   436→
   437→            <p>
   438→                <strong>Newton's Identities (<a href="./docs/ChebyshevCircles/NewtonIdentities.html" style="color: #3498db;">NewtonIdentities module</a>):</strong>
   439→                Establishes the relationship between power sums of roots and elementary symmetric polynomials (coefficients).
   440→                Specifically, if two monic polynomials have roots with matching power sums S<sub>1</sub>, S<sub>2</sub>, ..., S<sub>N</sub>,
   441→                then the polynomials have identical coefficients except possibly the constant term. This is the bridge that converts
   442→                power sum equality into polynomial equality up to a constant. The formalization handles the recursive structure
   443→                of Newton's identities and proves the converse direction needed: power sum agreement implies coefficient agreement.
   444→                This classical result from polynomial algebra is indispensable for connecting root properties to polynomial identity.
   445→            </p>
   446→
   447→            <h2>Getting Started</h2>
   448→
   449→            <p>
   450→                <strong>Prerequisites:</strong> Lean 4 (v4.25.0-rc2), basic familiarity with polynomials, complex numbers,
   451→                and trigonometric identities.
   452→            </p>
   453→
   454→            <p>
   455→                Clone the repository and build the project:
   456→            </p>
   457→
